{"summary":"All five amendments should be accepted. Four identify concrete correctness or resilience defects in the new retry/resume handling, and the remaining one identifies a real test-coverage gap around newly introduced failure-classification and retry-attempt reconstruction logic.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-16-0e453769","decision":"accept","rationale":"`execute_stage_with_retry` now uses `write_run_snapshot(...)?` in the retry-backoff path after persisting `stage_failed`. That means a transient snapshot-store write failure aborts the retry loop outright, even though this snapshot is only there to preserve resumability during the sleep window. It also bypasses the established `fail_run_result(...)` handling used for other snapshot-write failures, so failure accounting becomes inconsistent."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-93041ffb","decision":"accept","rationale":"The new logic is under-tested. `derive_resume_state` now reconstructs retry attempt state from journal events, but there is no direct test pinning that `will_retry=true` failures resume at `failed_attempt + 1`. `classify_exit_failure` also lacks direct coverage for its distinct branches, especially the signal/no-exit-code path and warning behavior. Existing surrounding tests cover some timeout and exit-127 behavior indirectly, but they do not lock these new branches tightly enough."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-2a388021","decision":"accept","rationale":"`retryable_failed_attempts` is keyed only by `(stage_id, cycle)`, but `advance_completion_round` revisits planning/final-review in the same cycle while resetting `attempt` to 1. Because `StageFailed` events also omit `completion_round`, a retryable failure from round 1 can contaminate round 2 and resume that logically fresh execution at a higher attempt number. That silently burns retry budget across separate completion rounds and is a real correctness defect."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-416a5110","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is the same root bug as `fr-16-0e453769`, viewed from the resume semantics. If the backoff snapshot write fails, the last durable state may remain the earlier `Running` snapshot, and the caller simply propagates the error. That can strand the run in a non-resumable `Running` state, which defeats the entire purpose of writing a failed snapshot before the backoff sleep. This path needs either best-effort handling with warning or the same `StageCommitFailed -> fail_run_result(...)` treatment used elsewhere."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-2b3da48b","decision":"accept","rationale":"For PATH-based execution, `resolve_binary` returns a bare command name, so `!binary.is_absolute()` is always true in the spawn error classifier. A `spawn()` `ErrorKind::NotFound` caused by a missing working directory or missing script interpreter will therefore be labeled `BinaryNotFound` even when the executable itself exists. That incorrectly turns an environmental or transient failure into a terminal one and can suppress retries."}]}